  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align=center cellpadding='3' width='85%'>
  <tr><td class='spti2'>PLAYER JOURNAL</td></tr>  <tr><td class='db'><font class='dbti'>Birth of Hate</font> - Nashuya</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'> </td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>Day and night do not exist for a city without a sun. Nashuya tells time by when she last ate. She follows the troll Omug resplendent in his tattered mail on his way to the Third Gate. She hopes that soon she will eat again. Omug was wrong to leave the foreign quarter, and even a troll may be killed by a Teir'Dal in the city of darkness.
<p>
The troll enters the tunnel to the Lodge of the Dead and is gone. Nashuya looks around wildly; how can this be? She screams as a calloused claw grips her shoulder and wracks her small frame in waves of agony; and dies.
<p>
Innoruuk tells her that her time has not yet come and she comes to life in Nektulos Forest. She burns with embarassment as she darts naked through the forest and the city. The troll Omug watches her as she dresses and both pay their respects to her corpse as it sinks into the ground.
<p>
"You are a fool, child," growls the troll. "There is naught but death in your future. I but the first to give you this gift. I can give you this gift again if you like."
<p>
"Nay, troll. Allow me instead to present you with my own gift: my hate. I have ample hate to spare, for you who have killed me this day. You whose speech is not proper for your race."
<p>
The troll grins widely. "And who is this that decides what is proper speech for me? But I am a knight of shadows, and I am called to my lord's service. Pray our paths do not cross again, or you will feel my touch." The troll rises, continues on pass the ghouls that guard the Lodge.
<p>
Nashuya edges past the grinning undead, her unwashed white hair catching on the spikes of the door. "Wait," she commands, but the troll is lost in shadows and is gone.
<p>
A leering necromancer challenges her. "What business, here in the Lodge? Why have you come? For what purpose do you disturb the Dead?"
<p>
"My reasons are my own. I am the daughter of a noble, you cannot treat me thus, leave me be and pray I forget your rudeness."
<p>
The necromancer grins at her from the hood of his shadowed robe. "I see your father has attired you as befits a noble's daughter; in rags. Your servants have prepared for you a feast of rat ears and spider legs, will you not dine? Go now."
<p>
"My father is lost, he has traveled to Kunark and is being held in Cabilis. Our family can scarce afford his ransom, but he will return and then will know why you detain me thus."
<p>
The necromancer removes two chips of bone from his pouch. "I know your father, he runs my errands. He serves me yet; here he is." He casts the bones to the floor and they rise from the dead. The skeleton laughs at Nashuya.
<p>
"What is your name?" asks the necromancer. The skeleton cries out, "My name is Kobartik, and Jehred is my Master!"
<p>
"Such was your father named," says Jehred. "You see that I do know you. You have no purpose here and your family has no power in this city, save to serve the Dead. Now go."
<p>
"I will not!" she cries. "Give to me the bones of my father!"
<p>
"You shall have them," he says. "Kobartik, kill for me your daughter." Kobartik's empty gaze turns to Nashuya as Jehred places a rusty dagger in its bony fingers.
<p>
Nashuya wrestles the decaying skeleton. Her strength is no match for the magically animated bones. Her father's dagger plunges into her hip and she falls to the ground. Nashuya's fury erupts in pain and hate. "DIE!" she screams, and the skeleton's bones fly apart. She gathers them together and limps from the Lodge, the necromancer saying nothing.
<p>
The troll Omug meets her by the gate. "Come with me, you are summoned to the Lodge of the Dead."
<p>
"I have been there, you have not welcomed me and Jehred has not welcomed me, but there I found my father and I have no more business there."
<p>
"You found your father there but your Father has found you," says Omug. "It is He who commands you now."
<p>
Nashuya packs the bones in her pack and follows the troll into the Lodge of the Dead. The necromancer is gone. Omug brings her to Nezzka Tolax, who does not look at her kindly. His steel armor scrapes as he motions for her to kneel before him.
<p>
"I will not," says Nashuya.
<p>
"You will," says Nezzka, and he clubs her with a mailed fist. Blood mats her hair on one side when she regains consciousness. Nezzka grins down at her. Omug holds a dark tunic and a tarnished short sword. "You are Innoruuk's now, child," says Nezzka. He points toward the items in Omug's arms. "Take this tunic and this sword. The tunic marks you as a child of Hate, for you are surely that. The sword marks you as a separator of souls. And your touch marks you as one filled with Innoruuk's dark power. For your crimes in this Lodge, you must leave this city. Do not return until you learn your place here."
<p>
She takes the tunic from Omug and pulls it over her head. She takes the sword and belts it to her waist. "I will return when you have learned your place. You will not die until you kneel at my feet, and then you will die and your bones will call me master."
<p>
"Even so," agrees Nezzka. "Leave now lest your bones serve me instead."
<p>
Omug grips her shoulder, but this time death does not follow. "Seek Raztara, my mother, in Grobb," he murmurs. "Tell her that her son abides. Pardon her rough speech. She will feed you and give you shelter. Return when your father walks by your side."
<p>
Nashuya nods and hurries from the city. She fights her way through dim Nektulos and away from her homeland and braves many dangers until she comes to the swamp of Innothule, wherein lies the froglok city of Guk and the troll city, Grobb.
<p>
Raztara weeps when she hears of her son. "Me boy gone many day now, he not call, he not write, he send inky to eat all my food n' drink, what he think, I run inn for lost inky here?"
<p>
"He does well, Mother Raztara, he slew me with a touch. He is powerful."
<p>
"Bah, smallest baby kill you wit one touch, that no problem. I not talk to you now. I tink about boy. You go kill froggy and find stuff to wear. I find rotted meat and rancid water for you. You grow strong like troll. Now you go."
<p>
Nashuya returns to the swamp and learns her Art fighting the frogloks, fungus and alligators there. She waits for the day when the bones she saves can protect her in death as they never did in life. Her hate simmers.
</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db2'><a href='view_profile.asp?Action=Journal&Id=25923'>Return to Nashuya's Journal</a></td></tr>
